

Semantic elements

          wo hote hain jin ko dekh kar hi yeh andaza lag jata hai ke yeh element kis kaam ke liye hai. Jaise ke:

<header> se samajh ata hai ke yeh page ka header yaani shuruat wala hissa hai.
<footer> se yeh pata chalta hai ke yeh page ka niche ka hissa hai.

In elements ka maqsad unke naam se hi wazeh hota hai, aur yeh SEO (search engine optimization) aur accessibility ke liye bhi helpful hote hain.

Readability: Code zyada readable hota hai aur doosray developers ya aap khud bhi code ko asaani se samajh sakte hain.

SEO (Search Engine Optimization): Search engines (jaise Google) ko bhi semantic elements se asaani hoti hai, kyun ke yeh sections samajhne mein madadgar hote hain.

Accessibility: Screen readers (jo visually impaired users ke liye hote hain) ko bhi yeh clear sections read karna zyada asaan hota hai.
; /////////////////////////////*******************************///////////////////////////////

Non-semantic elements 

            jaise ke <div> aur <span>, inka naam se yeh pata nahi chalta ke inka maqsad kya hai. Yeh bas layout banane ke liye use hote hain,
             aur inko kisi bhi cheez ke liye customize kiya ja sakta hai. Jaise ke, <div> kisi section ka design ya kisi aur kaam ke liye 
             use kiya ja sakta hai, lekin isme koi fixed meaning nahi hota.

             To semantic elements ka faida yeh hai ke yeh code ko zyada readable aur samajhne mein asaan banate hain, 
             jabke non-semantic elements zyada flexible  hote hain aur unko har tarah se use kiya ja sakta hai.




; /////////////////////////////*******************************///////////////////////////////


Agar  specific section ka clear purpose batana chahte hain, toh semantic elements ka use acha hota hai (jaise <header>, <footer>).
Agar  bas layout banane ya styling ke liye container chahiye, toh non-semantic elements jaise <div> zyada flexible aur suitable hote hain.

